00:04:57.300 --> 00:04:57.540
Yes.

00:04:58.660 --> 00:05:00.220
Roughly almost two years ago.

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:01.080
Yes.

00:05:01.240 --> 00:05:01.640
That's awesome.

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:06.560
You know, I do hear from a lot of people or see comments like, oh, I think I'm too old to learn this.

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:11.840
Or, oh, you have to have done this when you were a kid or maybe gotten a degree in college.

00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:13.140
Otherwise, you're doomed.

00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:18.640
You surely have an alternative viewpoint on that, given your success.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:28.540
Actually, I thought it would be like that also for me because I would say I'm quite a perfectionist.

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:32.740
So if I learn something, I want to achieve something with what I learn.

00:05:33.190 --> 00:05:49.160
And the problem, the issue with code for me for a long time had been that, okay, I could go through the basic tutorials, the first lessons, you know, watching some videos or reading some tutorials.

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:58.280
But it was difficult for me to really achieve something meaningful, something that I could really share that could become a product.

00:05:58.979 --> 00:06:01.960
because you always end up doing the same little, you know,

00:06:03.419 --> 00:06:07.540
exercises and little tutorials and that doesn't end up anywhere.

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:10.700
So you learned how to do a loop,

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:13.660
but then that doesn't really help you get any closer to an app, right?

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:17.120
You learn how to do a little to-do list or a little calculator

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:19.400
or, you know, something very simple,

00:06:19.560 --> 00:06:22.800
nothing that would be worth sharing as a product

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:24.200
and especially as a paid product.

00:06:24.400 --> 00:06:27.780
So I always thought, okay, if I want to build a SaaS,

00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:34.760
The only solution for me is to rely on a freelancer or on an agency or on a team of people.

00:06:35.919 --> 00:06:40.780
That's how I was doing it until I discovered it.

00:06:40.780 --> 00:06:41.540
And that's a big risk.

00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:54.420
And it's also not that easy to hire a team to build your product when you're still trying to figure out what a product is and all these things, right?

00:06:55.240 --> 00:06:55.380
Yes.

00:06:56.060 --> 00:06:59.680
I mean, even if you hire non-expensive developers,

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:01.720
it has still a cost.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:08.200
And if you don't want to take too much risk,

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:13.040
if you want to test your product to see if you have product market fits,

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:16.500
I mean, you don't want to spend $5,000, $10,000, $15,000 on a product.

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:20.200
So, yeah, it's difficult.

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:27.580
And the alternative that people are most of the time advocating these days,

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:28.440
it's no code.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:35.820
So it's building stuff with, let's say, Bubble, which is pretty popular.

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:39.760
You've got Retool.

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:41.580
They've been a sponsor of the show before.

00:07:42.680 --> 00:07:46.720
Retool, obviously, that's pretty nice, mostly for internal apps.

00:07:48.580 --> 00:07:53.960
And also, you can just connect stuff through Zapier, through Make,

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:55.300
formerly Integromat.

00:07:56.880 --> 00:08:02.060
So you can achieve something, but you don't have the control on the UI.

00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:06.000
You don't really have the control exactly on what's happening behind the scenes.

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:11.720
And you don't have the flexibility that you have if you really code yourself,

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:15.800
so if you can really get your hands dirty and code on your own.

00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:20.160
So I used also to be a strong advocate of no code.

00:08:20.350 --> 00:08:28.500
So I was using, and I'm still using, firstly Zapier and then later on Make.

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:39.180
But once I discovered Python in August, September 2022, then everything changed for me.

00:08:39.250 --> 00:08:42.680
Because then I could really start doing my own stuff.

00:08:42.860 --> 00:08:54.840
And I started with the backend stuff, with the backend scripts for, let's say, to create competitive intelligence scripts, things like that.

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:57.500
And I slowly moved into frontend.

00:08:57.720 --> 00:09:03.120
But first, for a few months, it was mostly local scripts on my computer.

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:06.580
Yeah, that's really interesting.

00:09:06.840 --> 00:09:09.880
The low-code, no-code stuff is super powerful.

00:09:10.460 --> 00:09:14.420
I think it does make it possible for people to build apps.

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:18.520
I have a friend who built a platform a little bit on top of something

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:20.520
that's kind of a low-code thing.

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:23.200
And what they're doing is really impressive.

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:27.100
And they've got lots of customers, and it's going really well.

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:28.120
It's a vibrant business.

00:09:30.200 --> 00:09:34.120
But it's always you're beholden to whatever that platform does.

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:36.500
If the platform has downtime, you have downtime.

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:43.020
they're changing their feature set in a way that doesn't quite line up with what you're trying to do.

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:48.520
Well, that's too bad because, you know, they've changed their direction or whatever.

00:09:48.680 --> 00:09:54.340
And it's really powerful, but it's also a little bit of a risk, right, to be built on top of that.

00:09:55.600 --> 00:09:56.460
A risk, yes.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:02.700
But for me, it was even more, I would say, the arbitrage was even more about flexibility.

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:12.820
So when you code something on your own with Python, JavaScript, as I'm doing now, it's

00:10:12.980 --> 00:10:19.220
faster in many cases than trying to figure out how to connect, let's say, Airtable with

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:19.880
something else.

00:10:20.150 --> 00:10:26.260
Then you've got to think about how the data is structured in Airtable, how the data has

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:30.600
to be structured on the other side, and then how to connect them together.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:38.540
Sometimes it's easier if you just have a SQLite database

00:10:38.770 --> 00:10:43.280
or MySQL database, and then if you do your own stuff on your own

00:10:43.430 --> 00:10:49.240
without trying to connect existing SaaS together.

00:10:50.100 --> 00:10:52.720
So it was more about flexibility for me,

00:10:54.570 --> 00:10:58.520
the main reason why I switched almost completely

00:10:58.530 --> 00:11:00.620
from no code to coding.

00:11:01.660 --> 00:11:07.340
that's really interesting i guess one more that would be worth considering is price some of these

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:13.180
low-code no-code platforms are really powerful but when you start to look at price for a decent

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:18.040
number of users using your app a lot of them are built for internal use cases they're not really

00:11:18.140 --> 00:11:24.699
built for having a bunch of multi-tenant style users and so on but also they can just get real

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:32.340
expensive real quick yes because they are based usually on the amount of transactions or scenarios

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:40.580
or zaps that that can you know run so if you want to transfer one piece of data from one software to

00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:47.600
another one it's one transaction so if you if you have let's say 10 000 transactions per month for

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:55.100
a certain price then yeah you can run out of transactions pretty quickly you know it's very

00:11:55.340 --> 00:12:03.740
quickly you you end up paying 25 30 40 dollars for you know a pretty low amount of transactions

00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:10.940
of api codes basically between the between the difference yeah and if you glue them together

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:19.860
in, you know, one tool connects to another, which connects to another, then you've got to pay for

00:12:20.040 --> 00:12:23.780
kind of the traffic and the activity in all three. It's not just like, well, I'm talking to my

00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:28.480
database. I'm now talking to some other service that's got, you know, something going on.

00:12:29.060 --> 00:12:39.259
Yes, yes, yes. And the fact is also that there are a few tools that enable you to create a UI

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:41.180
user interface for your product,

00:12:41.360 --> 00:12:43.880
but you're limited to the building blocks usually that they offer,

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.640
even if you can tweak them with some code.

00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:47.840
And it's a bit the same.

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:49.500
I would say it's really also the same issue

00:12:49.720 --> 00:12:53.600
that I've experienced on WordPress, let's say.

00:12:54.120 --> 00:12:58.280
The problem is that if you use something like Bubble

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:03.580
and you want to build something with it,

00:13:05.740 --> 00:13:08.920
you bring to your app all the mothership,

00:13:09.250 --> 00:13:13.720
the core of the big app, let's say,

00:13:14.050 --> 00:13:15.200
of Bubble as a whole,

00:13:15.770 --> 00:13:18.740
when you want to build something on top of a platform like that.

00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:24.500
So it's a lot of things that you don't really need

00:13:24.510 --> 00:13:25.640
for your specific apps,

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:28.920
but that have to be there because the whole engine has to run.

00:13:29.510 --> 00:13:31.340
Yeah, that's a good point.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:35.080
Usually what you also experience with WordPress, for instance,

00:13:35.910 --> 00:13:40.400
when you have a site on WordPress, maybe sometimes

00:13:40.550 --> 00:13:43.020
or even most of the time you don't need that big engine.

00:13:43.250 --> 00:13:47.060
You could work with a static website with a few HTML, CSS,

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:48.000
JavaScript pages.

00:13:48.130 --> 00:13:49.680
That would be much lighter.

00:13:49.810 --> 00:13:55.580
There would be less code to activate,

00:13:55.950 --> 00:13:59.080
to have your website up and running.

00:14:01.560 --> 00:14:03.920
So, yeah, it's also in terms of performance,

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:06.700
if you can code your own stuff,

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:12.660
I think it's also a good reason to choose coding versus no code

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:13.720
if you can do it.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:14.900
Totally agree.

00:14:15.240 --> 00:14:18.720
Price, performance, control, all those things.

00:14:19.380 --> 00:14:23.780
That said, you do have to understand more about the world.

00:14:24.720 --> 00:14:27.859
Like one thing we were coordinating around

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:31.840
is just like understanding web app architecture.

00:14:33.230 --> 00:14:34.720
I don't know how you feel about it,

00:14:34.720 --> 00:14:36.660
but I feel like a lot of the guidance

00:14:36.830 --> 00:14:40.120
that is out there is too intense.

00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:43.200
There's too many moving parts, right?

00:14:43.720 --> 00:14:45.260
Everyone thinks you need to have

